{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The conversation history passed to the LLM is trimmed to the most recent 10 messages when the full history exceeds the context window.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure boundary is module handoff: history selection + request builder + LLM client payload. MOCK-MISS: a pure unit test of a trim helper can pass while the wrong slice/order is sent by the caller. REAL-INFRA: no real OS/network/subprocess required; a stub LLM client in-process is sufficient, so not System. LLM-DEP: assertion is about which messages are sent, not model judgment, so not Agentic. MULTI-STEP: no multi-agentic sequence, so not Workflow.","test_description":"Wire chat orchestrator with real history-trimming module and a stub LLM transport that records outbound payload. Provide >10 prior messages with identifiable sequence, invoke response generation, and assert exactly the most recent 10 messages (correct order/roles) are sent to the LLM call.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The generated response addresses the customer's question rather than producing a generic or off-topic reply.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on real LLM output quality (relevance/on-topicness). MOCK-HIDE: stubbed responses would always satisfy assertions and cannot reveal off-topic generations. This is the deterministic-assertion trap: wrapper logic can be tested with fakes, but model decision quality cannot. Rejected Workflow because behavior describes one generation quality check, not a required multi-agentic pipeline.","test_description":"Run real model inference on a representative set of customer questions and score whether answers address asked intent (human rubric or calibrated evaluator). Fail if relevance/on-topic rate drops below threshold.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.0,"Agentic":0.83,"Workflow":0.06}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The tone re-check correctly identifies when a response is too formal for a casual-tier customer and triggers regeneration.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"The forcing phrase is \"correctly identifies\" tone mismatch, which depends on model judgment of tone suitability. MOCK-HIDE: mocked tone checker cannot expose misclassification. Integration is too low because pass/fail hinges on real AI/ML output content. Rejected Workflow: behavior can be validated with a fixed candidate response fed to the real tone-check model plus assertion that regeneration is invoked; it does not require validating quality across multiple model decisions in sequence.","test_description":"Submit a known overly formal candidate reply for a casual-tier customer to the real tone-check step in the live orchestration path; assert it is flagged and that regeneration call is executed.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.5,"Workflow":0.35}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The full exchange (user message, generated response, any regenerations) is persisted to the database with correct timestamps.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is cross-module state propagation into persistence (orchestrator -> logging/persistence layer -> DB schema). Needs real local DB wiring to catch mapping/transaction/timestamp bugs. REAL-INFRA check: no external network or OS-specific primitive required; local test DB suffices, so not System. LLM-DEP: content quality irrelevant; deterministic stubs for generations are enough, so not Agentic/Workflow.","test_description":"Run end-to-end application flow in-process with a real test database. Stub generation outputs to force both single-pass and regeneration paths. Assert persisted records include user input, all drafts/final response as specified, and timestamps populated/ordered correctly.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.07,"Integration":0.78,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the tone check triggers regeneration, the second response replaces the first — the customer never sees the rejected draft.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Primary risk is orchestration/state handoff bug between tone-check result, regeneration, and outbound response selection. This is multi-module flow and not just one function, so Unit is too low. REAL-INFRA: can be reproduced in-process without real OS/network/subprocess, so not System. Rejected Agentic/Workflow because behavior text is about replacement/visibility control (delivery semantics), not correctness of model judgment/content; trigger can be injected deterministically.","test_description":"Execute chat pipeline with tone-check forced to trigger and deterministic first/second drafts. Assert customer-facing output equals second draft only, while rejected first draft is withheld from delivery channel.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.22,"Workflow":0.12}}]}
